# [DISPATCH](../wg/dispatch.html)

**Session:** ART / SEC Joint Dispatch  
**IETF 120, Vancouver** (July 2024)  
**Chairs:** Shuping Peng, James Gould, Rifaf Itani  

## Summary
The ART/SEC Joint Dispatch session met to evaluate several new work proposals spanning URI schemes, AI agent security, mail filtering, and post-quantum cryptography. Due to significant technical difficulties with audio and remote participation, the Chairs and Area Directors (ADs) noted that definitive dispatch decisions for several items would be deferred or handled via the mailing list to ensure full community participation.

## Key Discussion Points

### [DONAU: A URI-scheme for tax-deductible donations](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-draft-grothoff-donau-00)
**Presenter:** Christian Grothoff  
**Draft:** `draft-grothoff-donau`

*   **Discussion:** The proposal defines a URI scheme to facilitate digital, tax-deductible donations. Christian Grothoff suggested it could lead to a broader "Payments BoF." Mark Nottingham questioned why this was a URI scheme rather than a data format and suggested coordination with the W3C. Eric Rescorla and Richard Barnes argued that the work did not belong in the IETF. Ted Hardie noted that while the provisional URI registration exists, no further IETF work is justified.
*   **Outcome:** No further work in the IETF; suggested coordination with W3C.

### [AI Agent Authentication and Authorization](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-ai-agent-authentication-and-authorization-00)
**Presenter:** Yaroslav Rosomakho  
**Draft:** `draft-rosomakho-ai-agent-auth` (Refenced as framework proposal)

*   **Discussion:** The draft proposes a framework using existing standards (OAuth, WIMSE) to provide guardrails for AI agents. Aaron Parecki and Brian Campbell clarified that the document is intended as a "menu" or map of existing specifications rather than a new protocol. Richard Barnes and the Chairs noted that audio issues prevented a full discussion with remote participants.
*   **Outcome:** No formal dispatch decision due to technical difficulties.

### [Well-Known URIs: Registration Policy Redux](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-well-known-uris-registration-policy-redux-00)
**Presenter:** Mark Nottingham  
**Reference:** RFC 8615

*   **Discussion:** Mark Nottingham (Designated Expert) raised concerns about "squatting" on attractive, generic names (e.g., `ai`, `agents`) in the `.well-known` registry. He proposed updating the registration policy to require more evidence of community buy-in. Ted Hardie and Harald Alvestrand suggested the expert has sufficient latitude under current text to "apply handbrakes" while a more formal update (potentially AD-sponsored) is considered.
*   **Outcome:** General support for the Expert to exercise more discretion; potential for an AD-sponsored update to RFC 8615.

### [Verifiable Agent Conversation Records](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-verifiable-agent-conversation-records-00)
**Presenter:** Hank Birkholz  
**Draft:** `draft-birkholz-verifiable-agent-conversation-records` (Referenced as [Verifiable Agent Conversation Records](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-verifiable-agent-conversation-records-00))

*   **Discussion:** The proposal seeks to standardize structured logs for AI interactions using CBOR/CDDL for verifiability and auditability. Richard Barnes and Eric Rescorla emphasized the need for clear vendor interest before proceeding. Thomas McCarthy-How suggested the work might fit within the **VCON** working group.
*   **Outcome:** "Press pause" until vendor support is demonstrated; further discussion with the VCON WG.

### [Cross-Platform Policy Parental Control (X-PPC) for Household Governance](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-cross-platform-policy-parental-control-x-ppc-for-household-governance-00)
**Presenter:** David (Presenter)

*   **Discussion:** The presenter proposed a unified API for managing parental controls across different device ecosystems (TVs, consoles, phones). Eric Rescorla and Richard Barnes noted that while the problem is real, IETF intervention requires participation from the major platform vendors who currently maintain siloed solutions.
*   **Outcome:** Dispatch to "nowhere" (no action) pending evidence of vendor interoperability interest.

### [MTA Hooks](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-mta-hooks-presentation-00)
**Presenter:** Mauro  
**Draft:** `draft-scalambra-mta-hooks`

*   **Discussion:** This proposal introduces an HTTP/JSON/CBOR-based replacement for the aging "Milter" protocol used in mail filtering. Barry Leiba suggested a BoF to discuss the underlying problem. Bron Gondwana and Alexey Melnikov expressed vendor interest, while others noted that buy-in from major open-source MTAs (Postfix, Sendmail, Exim) would be critical.
*   **Outcome:** Recommended for a BoF (Birds of a Feather) session, possibly for IETF 121 (Vienna).

### [Agent Interaction & Delegation Protocol](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-agent-interaction-delegation-protocol-00)
**Presenter:** Yiannis

*   **Discussion:** A control-plane protocol to decouple AI "reasoning" from deterministic system "execution" to ensure safety. Eric Rescorla noted the lack of current vendor implementation interest. Usama (TU Dresden) questioned the specific links to the EU AI Act and current high-stakes usage.
*   **Outcome:** No action until broader community/vendor energy is established.

### [Proof of Process (PoP): A Verified Process Transcript Format](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-proof-of-process-pop-a-verified-process-transcript-format-00)
**Presenter:** David Chaudhry  
**Draft:** `draft-chaudhry-rats-pop`

*   **Discussion:** The draft uses hardware-backed attestation and keystroke dynamics to prove a human was "at the keyboard" during content creation. Martin Thompson and Eric Rescorla expressed skepticism regarding the technical viability and whether this belongs in the RATS WG.
*   **Outcome:** Not appropriate for RATS; would require a BoF to demonstrate broad community interest and technical feasibility.

### [Security protocols that are optimized for non-web and PQC](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-dispatch-security-protocols-that-are-optimized-for-non-web-and-pqc-00)
**Presenter:** Russ Housley

*   **Discussion:** Russ Housley proposed using MLS-like continuous key agreement to mitigate the large overhead of Post-Quantum Cryptography (PQC) in bandwidth-constrained, non-web environments. Eric Rescorla and Richard Barnes requested a sharper performance analysis to justify the work.
*   **Outcome:** Create a new mailing list to refine requirements; target a BoF for IETF 121.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **MTA Hooks:** Recommended for a BoF.
*   **PQC for Non-Web:** Mailing list to be created; target a BoF.
*   **Well-Known URIs:** Mark Nottingham to continue exercising expert discretion; ADs to consider a focused update to RFC 8615.
*   **DONAU/X-PPC/Agent Interaction Protocol:** No IETF action at this time due to lack of vendor support or better fit elsewhere (W3C).

## Next Steps
*   The Area Directors will review the session's findings, particularly for items where technical issues hindered remote participation, and will provide final guidance on the DISPATCH mailing list.
*   Proponents for **MTA Hooks** and **PQC for Non-Web** should begin preparing BoF proposals for the next IETF meeting.